Headlines.Author: Tess Stynes
Headlines.Headline: UDR Names Industry Veteran Herzog as New CFO

PARAGRAPH.#text: UDR Inc. UDR named industry veteran Tom Herzog as the apartment real-estate investment trust's chief financial officer starting next month. Mr. Herzog's prior experience includes serving as CFO at Denver-based real-estate investment company Amstar, as well as health-care property company HCP Inc. HCP from 2009 to 2011 and Apartment Investment & Management Co. AIV, or Aimco, from 2005 to 2009. The company's former CFO, David L. Messenger, left UDR in May for an opportunity outside the company. He had been with UDR for 10 years, including four years as CFO.

Headlines.Headline: Aimco, Stockholders to Offer 11 Million Shares

PARAGRAPH.#text: Apartment Investment & Management Co. AIV has commenced an offering of 11 million shares of its common stock to raise funds to redeem preferred stock. The company is offering nine million shares while Chief Executive Terry Considine and a Considine family partnership are offering two million shares. The company had 121.4 million shares outstanding as of May 2. Shares slid 2.6% to $27.05 a share after hours. Through the close, the stock is up 21% so far this year. Multifamily properties have been the stars of the real-estate sector for more than a year, as Americans have favored renting homes instead of buying them, driving vacancy rates lower and allowing landlords to command higher rents.

Headlines.Headline: MARKET TALK: Raymond James Is Worried About Aimco's Traffic

PARAGRAPH.#text: 1:41 (Dow Jones) Apartment operator Aimco (AIV) gets downgraded to outperform from strong buy at Raymond James in the wake of the company disclosing during Friday's 3Q conference call that leasing traffic slumped in October. "This phenomenon is likely limited to Aimco due to its higher mix of lower-income tenants," says Raymond James. It adds, "This is certainly a development that must be monitored closely in the months ahead as rent pressures are building most acutely on households with stagnant incomes." The company's 3Q results were seen as solid, and executives tried telling industry watchers not to worry too much because about the traffic slump because "the most important part of our business is the renewal business." (dawn.wotapka@dowjones.com)

Headlines.Headline: Apartment Invest In Plan To Facilitate Stock Buyback

#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Apartment Investment and Management Co.

entered a stock trading plan to help the company buy back its Class A shares, according to a filing with the Securities and Exchange Commission Wednesday. Purchases under the plan will begin in January. There are no set number of shares to be bought, and the company may cancel the plan at any time. Apartment Investment, a real estate investment trust based in Denver, entered the stock trading plan under SEC Rule 10b5-1, which allows insiders to adopt agreements under which they can buy or sell their company's stock legally, even if they later acquire inside information.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Before the Bell: Cisco, AOL, Alstom, AMR

#text: Rumor-riled stock futures were lower after the CIA denied reports picked up from Iranian radio that Osama Bin Laden had been caught. The bellwether market stocks surged on the report, picked up by the BBC and AFX, but quickly shed gains. European and U.K. stocks remained lower. Cisco Systems

led volumes, last just below $13, but well off of lows to $12.84 on Instinet. Iraq uncertainties continued to weigh on currencies and surfaced again in cautious corporate outlooks from large engineering companies Alstom and Smiths Group

in Europe on Wednesday. The euro was comfortably holding the $1.10 mark; the forex markets and stock futures traders were keeping an eye on dollar-yen around 117 amid talk of official-level Japanese action to weaken the yen. The U.S. has delayed a second resolution vote on Iraq in the UN; reports that the U.K.'s support for the U.S. is unravelling added to the uncertainty in the markets. However, Britain denied a split as Prime Minister spoke to MPs in a robust debate on Iraq policy.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Radisys sees rocky first half

#text: Radisys Corp. (RSYS)

will likely take a hit Tuesday after warning its first- and second-quarter earnings
    results will fall short of expectations. The manufacturer of embedded computers expects a
    profit of 38 to 40 cents a share in the first quarter on revenue of $1 million to $1.5
    million. Radisys expects its second quarter to be "solidly profitable" with
    sales in the range of $28 million to $30 million. Prior to the announcement, the consensus
    estimate was 49 cents a share for the first quarter and 54 cents a share in the second
    quarter. Radisys said several customers have postponed or reduced orders, while its
    largest customer expects to place no orders in the second quarter amid excess inventory
    and slackening demand. "I also expect some weakness to carry into the third
    quarter," said Glen Myers, chief executive officer. Myers cited the large revenue
    decline and weaker-than-anticipated orders from chip equipment and contract manufacturing
    customers. However, Myers expects moderate order recovery in the third quarter to push
    revenue back into the $33-million to $37-million range. Shares closed down 1/4 at 31 5/8.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Radisys sees rocky first half

 is getting
out of the apartment business, and has agreed to sell the operations to a
Denver REIT for $350 million in stock and $460 million in assumed debt.

PARAGRAPH.#text:

rankings

Equity's rise is all the more striking because before this year, no
real-estate investment trust had cracked the top five.

Scares Wall Street

Some money managers
, tired of seeing
their small stocks crater as "momentum investors" sell at the slightest
disappointment, are now checking out other shareholders before investing in
a company. If they see too many momentum investors, they back off.
